# Design System: Button Component

## Overview

Buttons are used to trigger actions. They communicate what will happen when the user interacts with them.

## Variants

| Variant | Usage | Example |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Primary | Main actions | Submit, Save |
| Secondary | Alternative actions | Cancel, Back |
| Destructive | Dangerous actions | Delete, Remove |
| Ghost | Subtle actions | Learn more, View all |

## Sizes

Small
: Height 32px, font size 14px, padding 8px 12px

Medium
: Height 40px, font size 16px, padding 10px 16px

Large
: Height 48px, font size 18px, padding 12px 24px

## States

- **Default**: The resting state
- **Hover**: When the cursor is over the button
- **Active**: While being pressed
- **Focused**: When navigated to via keyboard
- **Disabled**: When the action is unavailable
- **Loading**: While an async action is in progress

## Usage Guidelines

N> Always use a verb or verb phrase for button labels. "Save changes" is better than "OK".

W> Avoid using more than one primary button per section. Too many calls to action confuse users.

!> Destructive buttons must always include a confirmation dialog.

## Code Example

```tsx
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button"

function SaveForm() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Button variant="primary" size="md">
        Save Changes
      </Button>
      <Button variant="secondary" size="md">
        Cancel
      </Button>
    </div>
  )
}
```

## Accessibility

- [ ] All buttons must have visible focus indicators
- [ ] Icon-only buttons must have an `aria-label`
- [ ] Loading buttons must announce state to screen readers
- [x] Color contrast meets WCAG AA requirements
- [x] Touch targets are at least 44x44px
